The EU land set aside restores nature‚Äôs powers over the climate, fixing carbon dioxide and stabilising temperatures and rainfall. Carbon dioxide is not the demon, it is plant food and plants work for us providing us with food and controlling our climate to be most favourable for life. Carbon dioxide and fossil fuels are just side actors, just like police cars and ambulances are to accident scenes. Just because police cars and ambulances are present at every accident scene does not mean that they caused them. The same with carbon dioxide and fossil fuels, they were mere agents of deforestation but deforestation was the cause of environmental changes.

text:
¬†@Jan Adkins-Pont¬† As a foreigner, having learned English fluently early on through the Internet, The Canterbury Tales was one of the greatest works I'd read at that point, and made me truly understand how amazing English is for literary expression. It's a crap language for getting any work done, since technical terms all blend together due to the simplified phonetic system and complex grammar and etymology, but by God does it allow some downright gymnastic feats in regards to symbolism.

If you really want to see English at its very best, read Morals and Dogma by Albert Pike, it's a book on freemasonic symbolism and thought, and every paragraph has several layers of meaning with the simplest and most melodic language (and no doubt many more I miss with every read).

English, when properly used, is food for the mind, while my own language, much more specific and structured, is food for the soul.

text: I don't believe most of you understand why affirmative action was originally put into place... It was actually difficult for minorities and women to get ahead back in the day because of the prevailing attitudes of the time (minorities were less than, women were too emotional or incompetent and belonged in the kitchen, etc). Affirmative action, essentially, was meant to prohibit discrimination and create more opportunity for people who wouldn't have had it otherwise. When you look at things like tens of thousands of low income individuals (many Filipinos) being pushed out of their neighborhood in San Francisco so they could "Manhattanize" the downtown area (read: GENTRIFY) it definitely shows you something is wrong. It's not enough to displace the people who were native to this land, now you (referring to those in charge of that project and others like it) have to displace low-income individuals and minorites because you're greedy and those who aren't white aren't important? Read about how back in the day, there were many barriers (INTENTIONAL barriers‚Äîread: systemic racism) to black people that made it difficult to receive welfare. Read about how just having what some perceive as an "ethnic-sounding" name, even to this day, decreases the likelihood of getting a call for a job interview over Natalie or George or Amy when Shaniqua or Zuleika or Jamal are equally qualified. Let's talk about how women are less likely to be viewed as competent in leadership positions or positions of great responsibility, or maybe how they're less likely to be taken seriously when presenting to an emergency room with symptoms (on average men are given pain medication sooner than women, btw), and if you're a female AND a minority? Forget about it. You're mad because you feel you have to work harder to get into school or get a job because you think affirmative action is just preferential treatment of unqualified or underqualified minorities that works against whites? No, it's just meant to level the playing field that has always been in favor of white people. Minorities had to work hard for YEARS AND YEARS to still not get fully equal treatment. Affirmative action will never be to white people what life in general has ALWAYS been for everyone else.

text:
Climate Change is real, it's just not from mankind, but from orbit.  It used to be a debate before the propaganda empire ramped up in 2016ish.
It's referred to as Milankovitch cycles, cycling the planet periodically through multiple ice ages/glacial periods.
The Earth doesn't follow the exact same path around the Sun always and forever, slight variations over thousands of years cycle the planet between glacial and non-glacial periods over thousands of years.
A google image search of "milankovitch cycles graph" - the one with the orange background linking to a students paper is easy and non-convoluted to read.  You can see the present temperature dotted line running horizontally across the graph, as well as temperature peaks - much much warmer than today - periodically at about 115K, 235K, and 330,000 years ago - before mankind even existed.
The GH effect needs heat trapped to work, as that's what it is.  A car parked in the Sun has heat enter, get trapped, and swamps up the car extra hot via GH effect.
The Earth is not like this, it's like a car with it's windows rolled down, releasing heat constantly into space.  The Earth is not some bubble that keeps all the heat in.
The main source of heat is basic land/water heat retention.  For 12 hours of daylight, the land/water absorbs heat.  For 12 hours at night, the land/water releases heat.  "Average temperature" at any given time, is the equilibrium of absorbing heat/releasing heat - to give you average temperature range the Earth stays at.

When they forced (and they had to force it) the integration of the schools and bussing, there was a lot of tension and were a lot of fights. 

My mother wasn‚Äôt in that great of health (she passed away when I was 9) and we had a lady who came to our home during the week and helped her with the house, cooking, and the four of us. We loved that woman like a grandmother. I distinctly remember her refusing to sit down to supper with us and refusing to ride in the front seat of the car when Mama took her home, no matter how much Mama begged. text:
They got the wrong bloke.
The Democrats finally managed to impeach Donald Trump, by claiming two topics mentioned in a telephone call to the prime minister of Ukraine (Volodimir Zelensky) were the components of a quid pro quo deal. Only the most dishonest, and partisan interpretation could find such a connection between the two topics. But the Democrats did. The quid pro quo deal was one billion dollars of American money to replace one public prosecutor with another. I assume Joe Biden was an enthusiastic advocate of the quid pro quo theory. But simultaneously, circulating on Youtube, was a video of Joe Biden admitting striking the very same quid pro quo deal with a former prime minister of the Ukraine, namely one billion dollars of American money to replace a Ukrainian public prosecutor with a new one. Indeed, Joe Biden had developed the incident into an amusing anecdote, and was now BOASTING about it for the amusement of his fellow Democrats. In this case, there could be no doubt that the incident was a quid pro quo deal, because it was the very basis of Biden's anecdote. Moreover, Biden had a personal interest in removing this public prosecutor. The prosecutor was about to investigate the affairs of Burisma, the Ukrainian energy company in which Biden's son, Hunter Biden was (unaccountably) on the board of directors. 

I am not a US citizen, myself. But I would enjoy seeing the Democrats hoisted on the same petard which they spent so much time and effort trying to erect for Donald Trump.

I'm not sure about the rest of the world. There are a lot of people who are anti-Trump and will call him and his supporters racists and idiots. But I get that a lot when I'm talking to even family members in the US; mostly the younger generations. When I talk to family outside of the US, there is a much more positive favourable view on Trump. And many of the news bits I watch from Europe, Asia, and Australia mirror that view.

I didn't start off as a Trump supporter. Not sure if I would call myself one even now. When he won the election, I just wished he'd do a good job and had high hopes that he would be able to pull off what the professional politicians couldn't or wouldn't. Then years of seeing him being bashed by the MSM pressed me to find the other side of the story; because there ALWAYS is at least two sides to a story. What I found led me to go in search of other views from other parts of the world. My stand today leaning more toward pro-Trump is the result of believing that he actually did a good job, actually did what he said he would do (how many politicians can say that?), and countering the left movements because I see too much of communism tactics and ideologies in them.
